TI  - Associations between metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease and adverse clinical outcomes in chronic kidney disease: a prospective cohort study
T2  - HEPATOBILIARY SURGERY AND NUTRITION
AB  - Background: Metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease (MASLD) often co-exists with chronic kidney disease (CKD), but its long-term effects remain unclear. This study aims to evaluate the impact of MASLD on disease progression, cardiovascular risk, and all-cause mortality in CKD patients. Methods: This study included 2,277 participants with non-dialysis CKD at baseline in the Shanghai Suburban Adult Cohort and Biobank study [2016-2017]. Participants with pre-existing end-stage renal disease (ESRD) were excluded. MASLD was diagnosed by ultrasonographic steatosis with >= 1 metabolic risk factor (excluding cirrhosis). Participants were followed through electronic linkage to hospital and death records until death or 31 March 2024. Cox proportional hazards models were used to estimate the hazard ratios (HRs) for the associations between MASLD and incident ESRD, cardiovascular events (CVEs), and all-cause mortality. Restricted cubic splines were also applied to examine the associations between MASLDrelated cardiometabolic risk factors and the outcomes. Results: The co-prevalence of MASLD was 46.51%. Over a median 7-year follow-up, there were 409 ESRD cases, 1,288 all-cause CVEs, 901 coronary heart diseases (CHDs), 894 strokes, and 161 allcause deaths. MASLD was associated with higher risks of ESRD [HR =1.27, 95% confidence interval (CI): 1.05-1.55, P=0.02], all-cause CVEs (HR =1.29, 95% CI: 1.15-1.44, P<0.001), CHD (HR =1.29, 95% CI: 1.13-1.47, P<0.001), and stroke (HR =1.21, 95% CI: 1.06-1.38, P=0.005), but not all-cause mortality (P=0.39). MASLD remained associated with all-cause CVEs after adjusting for metabolic comorbidities (HR =1.15, 95% CI: 1.02-1.30, P=0.03). Risks of ESRD and all-cause CVEs also increased with higher waist circumference, elevated glycated hemoglobin levels, and reduced high-density lipoprotein-cholesterol levels. Conclusions: CKD patients coexisting with MASLD are at a higher risk of progressing to ESRD and developing incident CVEs. The findings highlight the importance of MASLD screening and cardiometabolic risk management in CKD patients.
